<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jailed Medellin Cartel Members To Be Transferred </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1703014594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2350 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1703014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 16 MAR (EFE) -- The Emisoras 
Caracol Network has reported that "within the next few hours" 
four lieutenants of the late Medellin Cartel boss Pablo Escobar 
will be transferred to Itagui Maximum Security Prison in the 
northwestern part of the nation. 
  A Caracol correspondent has reported that inmates Gustavo 
Adolfo Gutierrez Arrubla (alias Maxwell and La Trapeadora), Luis 
Carlos Aguilar Gallego (El Mugre), Jose Fernando Posadas Fierro, 
and Carlos Mario Alzate Urquijo (Arete) are scheduled to be 
transferred to Itagui. On 8 December 1993, the four confessed 
drug-traffickers were unexpectedly transferred to Santa Fe de 
Bogota's La Picota Prison. 
  The Caracol Network reports the inmates are being 
transferred 
to Itagui "despite recommendations against such a move by the 
national government." Two weeks ago, a conflict arose between 
Colombia's justice minister and the nation's prosecutor general 
because the minister opposed the order to transfer the inmates 
to another prison, warning that the transfer could help the 
dismantled Medellin Cartel reunite despite Pablo Escobar's 
December 1993 death. 
  Meanwhile in Medellin, it has been reported that the widow 
of 
Pablo Escobar, Victoria Henao, today visited her brother-in-law 
Roberto, alias Osito, at Itagui Prison. Victoria Henao traveled 
with her son Juan Pablo from her home in the Colombian capital 
to Medellin, where she stayed only a few hours. In the 
afternoon she returned to the Colombian capital aboard a charter 
flight. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

