<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Maritime Delimitation Treaty With Jamaica Ratified </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1603163594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2328 GMT 14 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1603163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 14 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- The 
Colombian and Jamaican Governments have ratified the Maritime 
Delimitation Treaty, which establishes a common area for the 
joint control and exploitation of marine flora and fauna. 
Jamaican Ambassador to Colombia Mattew Antoni Cox Beaubrun and 
Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin signed the document restating both 
governments' desire to jointly manage marine resources. 
  According to the document, the common area excludes the 
maritime zone around the Serranilla and Bajo Nuevo Banks 
because, in accordance with international law, that area is 
considered to be part of Colombian territory. In this manner, 
Colombia and Jamaica will be able to exploit the reserves or 
hydrocarbon fields that might be found in the designated area, 
and which might intersect the maritime border. 
  The treaty, ratified on 14 March, was signed in Kingston, 
Jamaica on 12 November 1993, after 19 years of negotiations 
between representatives from both nations. Known as the 
Sanin-Robertson Treaty, the agreement establishes a maritime 
delimitation line between Colombian territory, a common area 
located between the San Andres and Providence Archipelago, and 
Jamaican territory. 
  President Cesar Gaviria called the agreement "historic," and 
noted: "It will not only mark our boundaries in the Caribbean 
sea, but it will make us true neighbors." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

