<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Police Open Finance Ministry Doors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1603220494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1812 GMT 15 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1603220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 15 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- The National 
Police intervened today at the Finance Ministry offices, opening 
the doors of an institution whose employees have been on strike 
since 14 March demanding a salary increase. President de Leon 
Carpio issued the order today before leaving for Mexico on a 
two-day official visit, during which he will meet with Mexican 
counterpart Carlos Salinas de Gortari. 
  The National Police also plan to intervene in the next few 
hours at the courts of justice, the Supreme Court, and attorney 
offices, the employees of which have been on strike since 11 
March, demanding a 40-percent salary increase. 
  Public security agents have been posted at the main gates of 
the Finance Ministry to keep them open and to allow entry for 
people who want to pay their debts to the Treasury. 
  Last night, de Leon Carpio signed an agreement with the 
National Federation of Public Employees Unions to establish a 
monthly bonus for public employees of 110 quetzales, or the 
equivalent of $17. 
  The largest unions in the country, such as the Workers 
Unitary Organization [IUT] and the National Federation of State 
Workers Unions [Fenasteg], did not sign the agreement. IUT and 
Fenasteg proposed that the salary increase amount to 300 
quetzales, or $52, which the government rejected on the basis 
that it does not have enough funds to give public employees a 
salary increase. Public employees earn some $82 a month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

