<H3> <TI>   PT Linked to Illegal Italian Political Funding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1203022094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
11 Mar 94 p 6--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1203022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "JB Report" column by Teodomiro Braga] </F>
  [Text] The Workers Party [PT] is the target of the 
bombastic charge made in Rome on 8 March by Rio de Janeiro Judge 
Carlos Amorim. 
  Amorim charged that a Brazilian party has received money 
from 
the Italian mafia, but he declined to reveal the name of the 
party involved. PT members themselves, however, believe that 
Amorim was referring to the PT. 
  Luiz Salomao, leader of the PDT [Democratic Labor Party] 
bloc 
in the Chamber of Deputies, added more fuel to the fire by 
proposing the creation of an ad hoc committee to probe into the 
charge made by the judge, who will be called to testify. 
  PT leaders have described the charge as another fabrication 
designed to undermine the presidential candidacy of Lula [PT 
leader Luiz Inacio da Silva], and noted the connection existing 
between Amorim and [PDT leader and Rio de Janeiro Governor 
Leonel] Brizola. 
  The suspicion stems from the fact that it was Brizola who 
during his first term in office appointed Amorim to the Rio de 
Janeiro bench. 
  The charge caused excitement in the camps of other Lula 
adversaries, who speculated about further charges of foreign aid 
to the PT. 
  Associates of union leader Luiz Antonio Medeiros have stated 
that Medeiros has evidence of the transfer of funds to the PT 
from the Communist Party of the now defunct GDR. 

</TEXT>

