<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Import Tariffs Reduced To Force Price Drop </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103215894 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
10 Mar 94 Economic Section p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1103215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Finance Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso announced 
on 9 March that import tariffs on a long list of products that 
are manufactured by sectors that are run by oligopolies will be 
reduced to 2 percent. This is the government reaction to the 
indifference shown by the oligopolies to the stabilization plan 
and to excessive price increases. The list includes food 
products (canned food in general), cleaning and hygiene products 
(razor blades, toothpaste, tooth brushes, etc.), tires, ink, 
dyes, varnish, and chemicals used for the production of 
medicines. The minister said: "This measure will solve this 
problem. The country cannot bear speculation. Speculators will 
see that the government will take a firm line." 
  The measure is a victory for the group within the government 
which advocates stronger intervention to check price increases, 
over another more liberal group which managed to shelve a 
provisional measure that sought to regulate action against 
abuses. 
  Minister Cardoso said the government saw that prices of 
products whose import tariffs will be reduced were increased far 
beyond the inflation rate of the past 12 months. Cardoso said 
the resolutions to reduc these tariffs -- there are 
approximately 20 -- will be published in today's official 
gazette. Consequently, as of today importers will be able to 
bring those products to the domestic market at lower prices. 
  Cardoso said: "I believe this measure will send a strong 
signal that the government is determined to prevent 
speculation." Beside reducing customs tariffs, the government 
will enforce measures to de-bureaucratize imports and facilitate 
the purchase of foreign products. 
  The government published in yesterday's official gazette a 
list of 33 chemicals used for manufacturing medicines whose 
import tariffs were reduced to zero. The measure is valid until 
31 December 1994, because Mercosur [Common Market of the South] 
regulations will come into force on 1 January 1995. 
  Jose Milton Dallari, a special adviser to Minister Cardoso 
and a member of the so-called more liberal group within the 
government, does not support a control on the prices of 
oligopolies' products. He said: "If I go to a supermarket and 
protested against price increases, what would happen? Nothing, 
because people are tired of it." He says this is the main 
reason why he supports negotiating abusive price increases, 
discarding the idea of imprisonment, which Minister Cardoso has 
advocated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11114 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat051__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-051-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 March 1993 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Continues Visit to Asian Countries </TI></H3>
<H4>   Accord Signed in Indonesia </H4>
<F P=102> PA1003161294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1328 GMT 9 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1003161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, 9 Mar (PL) -- Foreign Ministers Roberto 
Robaina of Cuba and Ali Abdullah Alatas of Indonesia ratified 
documents here on a new commercial and economic cooperation 
agreement, which is expected to contribute to strengthening the 
ties between Cuba and Indonesia. 
  The exchange of protocols followed a meeting between Robaina 
and Indonesian Trade Minister Satrio Budihardjo Joedono. 
Robaina arrived in Jakarta last night on the first leg of a 
three-week visit to the Asian region that will take him to Laos, 
Myanmar (former Burma), Cambodia, India, Vietnam, and Malaysia. 
  During a news conference following the signing of the 
agreements, the Cuban official affirmed that his visit to the 
region seeks to explain the situation his country experiencing. 
  Robaina indicated that Asia needs to know what Cuba is and 
that we need to know about this continent. That is the reason we 
are making a big effort to bring an end to the unjust U.S. 
blockade against our country, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

