<H3> <TI>   Colombian Reports of Guerrilla Summit Refuted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1403150794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1829 GMT 13 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1403150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 13 Mar (PL) -- Today, the weekly JUVENTUD 
REBELDE denied Colombian daily EL TIEMPO reports of a meeting of 
Colombian guerrillas in Cuba and the existence of an office of 
Colombian rebels in Havana. 
  JUVENTUD REBELDE carried a lengthy report entitled Neither 
an Office, Nor a Rebel Summit in Havana, refuting the reports 
published by the Colombian newspaper on 10 March based on 
sources it never identifies. 
  The report added that one does not have to be Sherlock 
Holmes 
"to see EL TIEMPO's wicked intentions of trying to start a 
scandal" shortly after the Colombian Government announced its 
decision to sell 15,000 to 20,000 barrels of oil per day to Cuba. 
  JUVENTUD REBELDE said the lies published by EL TIEMPO also 
coincide with attacks against the trade agreement by Alexander 
Watson, U.S. assistant secretary of state for inter-American 
affairs. 
  A JUVENTUD REBELDE reporter visited the building in Havana's 
Alamar neighborhood, in Habana del Este Municipality, where 
according to EL TIEMPO, the rebels reportedly had an office, 
which residents in the area denied. 
  It is a building like any other, said Chilean painter Tato 
Aires, who has been living at D-2 in Zone Seven of that 
neighborhood for the past two months. 
  Several Latin American families live in the building, which 
the Cuban Institute of Friendship with Peoples (ICAP) made 
available to them while they are residing in Cuba. 
  One of the tenants is Colombian citizen Alexander Salcedo, 
20, who is studying medicine in Cuba thanks to his father's 
efforts, who has been receiving medical treatment in Cuba for 
the past six years. 
  Salcedo said there is no guerrilla office in that building, 
adding that he has no links with rebels or political parties in 
his country. 
  JUVENTUD REBELDE also noted that none of the Colombian 
guerrilla commanders mentioned by EL TIEMPO are on the 
participants list of a meeting of nongovernment, social, and 
human rights organizations held here two months ago. 
  The publication stressed that while EL TIEMPO publishes 
those 
lies, it omits reports of attacks by ultraright sectors of Cuban 
immigrants in Miami against Colombian citizens. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

