<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Secretary: Cuba's Readmission `Must Be Considered' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1903200294 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1549 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1903200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 19 Mar (NA) -- OAS Secretary General 
Joao Baena Soares said that the most disquieting issue for the 
OAS is "persistent extreme poverty" and that Cuba's readmission 
to the OAS "must be considered." 
  Baena said: "Issues such as the gap between those having too 
much and those having nothing and the lack of equal 
opportunities must be addressed to consolidate democracy." 
  He said: "I have noticed that there is growing awareness of 
this problem among governments, which appear to have the 
political will to address it in an orderly fashion." 
  Commenting on Cuba's readmission to the OAS, Baena said the 
issue "is generally discussed in the hallways" of the OAS. 
  Baena noted that there are two positions on the subject: On 
the one hand, there are those contending that "the time has come 
to review the situation," while on the other there are 
governments, such as that of the United States, that "contend 
that first there must be internal changes in Cuba before 
reconsidering its readmission." 
  Baena said he is in favor of revising the Inter-American 
Reciprocal Assistance Treaty (TIAR), which was unsuccessfully 
invoked by Argentina to obtain U.S. help during the Malvinas War. 
  Baena, who is a Brazilian diplomat, added: "Just as the OAS 
amended its charter three times during the past 10 years, it is 
necessary to revise the TIAR, which was signed under very 
different circumstances than those prevailing today. We must 
give new answers for new circumstances." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11219 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat054bb_94002" </HT>


