<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   TSE Releases Preliminary Election Results </TI></H3>
<H4>   FMLN Envoy: ARENA Bought Votes </H4>
<F P=102> PA2103151394 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL in Spanish 1350 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2103151394 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSKL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, Sergio Cerbello, Farabundo Marti National 
Liberation Front [FMLN] representative to Europe, accused the 
Nationalist Republican Alliance [ARENA] of buying votes in the 
20 March elections in El Salvador. Cerbello, who gave an 
interview following a telephone conversation with Ruben Zamora, 
candidate for the leftist coalition which also includes the 
FMLN, expressed his confidence that a second round will be 
necessary to elect a president because none of the candidates 
have won an absolute majority. 
  Sergio Cerbello, who is in Madrid at the invitation of the 
Spanish United Left coalition (led by the Spanish Communist 
Party), expressed surprise for victory statements made by ARENA, 
the official party, since the Supreme Electoral Tribunal has not 
released definitive results yet. 
  In light of the high abstentionism rate registered during 
the 
elections -- approximately 47 percent -- Cerbello said "it was 
the same as other elections held in the past ten years." 
Therefore, both the left and the right should concede that "they 
have not been able to motivate the people to vote." 
  Regarding leftist candidate Ruben Zamora's chances vis-a-vis 
ARENA candidate Armando Calderon in a possible runoff for the 
presidency, Cerbello said that "it all depends on the Christian 
Democracy Party [PDC]. The PDC representative in Europe has 
guaranteed me that the PDC will support Ruben Zamora, but they 
cannot guarantee people will comply with the party's 
instructions." 
  Cerbello announced that if the need for a second round is 
confirmed, Julio Anguita, leader of the Spanish United Left 
coalition, will travel to El Salvador to support Ruben Zamora in 
his race for the presidency. 

</TEXT>

