<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Dispute Election `Irregularities' 20 Mar </TI></H3>
<H4>   TSE Denies Soldiers at Polls </H4>
<F P=102> PA2003224194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2155 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2003224194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 20 Mar (ACAN) -- The Supreme Electoral 
Tribunal (TSE) denied today there are soldiers outside their 
barracks in reply to left-wing claims about a military presence 
at certain polling stations. 
  TSE Magistrate Eduardo Colindres told ACAN-EFE at the voting 
sites [colegios electorales] "the police are tasked with looking 
after the people's safety, and I can assure you the Army is not 
there." 
  Shortly after the general elections started today in El 
Salvador, Ruben Zamora, presidential candidate for the leftist 
coalition, which comprises former guerrillas and the Social 
Democracy, claimed soldiers were present in seven countryside 
towns, although this is banned by the Electoral Law. 
  Francisco Flores, deputy candidate for the ruling 
Nationalist 
Republican Alliance (right-wing ARENA), also told ACAN-EFE there 
is no military presence in the countryside but added certain 
policemen are clad in olive-green uniforms, and this makes them 
resemble soldiers. Flores said "this does not imply an Army 
presence." 
  At least 2.5 million Salvadorans will elect today, in the 
first elections since the civil war ended, a new president and 
vice president, 84 deputies to the Legislative Assembly, 262 
municipal mayors, and 20 representatives to the Central American 
Parliament (Parlacen). 
  The TSE, government, political parties, and UN observers 
have 
reported the elections have progressed normally so far, without 
any serious incidents. 

</TEXT>

