<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   TSE Says Second Election Round Possible 24 Apr </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003141994 San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY in Spanish 19 Mar 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PA2003141994 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) reported that 
in the event there is no absolute winner in the 20 March 
presidential elections, a second electoral round is scheduled 
for 24 April. TSE President Dr. Arturo Zaldivar said the TSE has 
everything ready for a second round. 
  Political party representatives who were asked, however, 
listed the inconveniences a second round would cause. Therefore, 
they have asked citizens to make every effort to vote on Sunday 
to decide once and for all their future. A second round would 
cause generalized uncertainty, directly affecting investments. 
Likewise, new elections would freeze bureaucratic work. Just 
organizing a second round would cost millions [currency not 
specified]. The parties would have to spend money on new 
propaganda. Citizens would be again exposed to partisan 
propaganda. Voters would have to face further discomfort. 
  Zaldivar, on the other hand, rejected a possible FMLN 
[Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front] election challenge 
in Chalatenango Department. The FMLN are dissatisfied about 
concentrating four municipality voting sites in the department's 
capital. Zaldivar said it is not true that the UN is pressuring 
them to leave the polling stations in Arcatao, San Jose las 
Flores, Nueva Trinidad, and San Isidro Labrador. "We do not 
accept domestic or foreign pressures," the official stated. 
  He said the FMLN has no possibility of challenging the 
elections there because the TSE is in compliance with the law. 
On this Zaldivar said: "Challenges are made when the law is 
disregarded. We are obeying the law." He added that the general 
rule is that voting should occur in the municipalities but the 
same law covers exceptions. It states that voting places may be 
changed due to unforeseen circumstances or in rare cases. Other 
voting places have also been changed, like San Francisco Gotera, 
which was moved to Cara Sucia, and Colon, which will be moved to 
Lourdes. "In these cases, nothing was said because there is 
simply no political interest," Zaldivar said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

