<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon Denies Request for Security Force Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003040594 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 18 Mar 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA2003040594 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] President Ramiro De Leon Carpio warned that 
"towns will not be allowed to go without civilian or military 
authorities." He was referring to Santa Lucia Cotzumalguapa, 
Escuintla, and San Lucas Toliman municipalities, Solola 
Department, whose residents seek the withdrawal of security 
forces. 
  Upon returning from a three-day trip to Mexico, De Leon 
Carpio attributed the residents' dissatisfaction with the 
authorities to several causes, including social corruption, and 
the fact that justice is not properly managed. The president 
explained that many of the irregularities that delay law 
enforcement will be corrected when the new Penal Code goes into 
effect, but he emphasized that the problem lies not only in the 
laws but in the human element as well. 
  We have training programs for law enforcement personnel 
which 
will guarantee a change in the current situation, but there are 
other elements outside justice management that prevent the 
normal governing of the country. 
  The people's discontent in those areas where the security 
forces have been asked to withdraw is understandable if we 
consider that the citizens' attitudes are affected by other 
factors such as poverty, injustice, and social disorder. 
  The president described his trip to Mexico as positive in 
every respect and said he worked with a full agenda for several 
exhausting but satisfying days to achieve the benefits obtained 
for our country. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

