<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Denials Issued on Guerrillas at `Summit' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government Confirms Denial </H4>
<F P=102> PA1803152494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0142 GMT 18 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1803152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 17 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Cuba confirmed today its 
denial of an alleged Colombian guerrilla "summit" in Havana 
after the government of the South American country stated it had 
"firm indications" of the encounter. 
  "It is all false; it is untrue a guerrilla summit was held 
in 
Cuba," Jose Ramon Balaguer, who is in charge of international 
relations of the ruling Communist Party's Politburo, told 
NOTIMEX. 
  Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin said on Thursday in 
Santa Fe de Bogota she had requested an official explanation 
from Cuba in light of the "firm indications" she had of the 
meeting, although President Cesar Gaviria subsequently explained 
the request was being processed. 
  President Cesar Gaviria added Colombia's relations with Cuba 
now depend on Havana's response to the petition for an 
explanation on the case. 
  the Cuban Foreign Ministry on Thursday morning denied having 
received the note mentioned by Sanin. 
  "We hold in high esteem our relations with Colombia, and in 
no way could something of that sort have occurred," Balaguer 
said regarding the alleged meeting. 
  The political leader said the version of the meeting 
published in the Colombian daily EL TIEMPO is "an attempt to mar 
relations" between the two nations, which "were being developed 
earnestly and can continue to develop." 
  The media report on a meeting in the Cuban capital among 
Colombian guerrillas was published five months after the two 
nations had resumed diplomatic relations. 
  The media version followed the announcement made by the 
Colombian Government on negotiations that will lead to the sale 
of 15,000 to 20,000 barrels of petroleum to Cuba, which for 
three decades has been under a U.S. trade embargo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

