<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Official Cited on Decision To Sell Oil </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1903192594 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1900 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1903192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombian Minister of Mines and Energy Guido Nule 
reiterated the decision of the Colombian Government to sell 
15,000 to 20,000 barrels of oil daily to Cuba as agreed during a 
recent visit by Nule to Havana. Nule stated: The deal stands, 
and the only thing missing is for Cuba to present the 
corresponding guarantees because we are talking about a business 
deal as any other where there is a buyer and a seller. 
  Minister Nule pointed out that Colombia sells oil to anyone 
who pays for the oil in cash and at international prices. Nule 
dismissed threats by Cuban emigre extremists in Miami, who 
threatened to boycott Colombian products in the United States in 
retaliation for selling oil to Cuba. 

</TEXT>

