<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plenum Held on Parliaments in the Workplace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lazo, Ross Attend Plenum </H4>
<F P=102> FL2103011294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2103011294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Santiago de Cuba correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Esteban Lazo Hernandez, member of the Politburo and 
first secretary of the Communist Party of Cuba [PCC] in Santiago 
de Cuba Province, said this afternoon that the principal 
importance of the Parliaments in the Workplace process has been 
the working class' discussion of how to save its oeuvre. He said 
this during the plenum concluding the process in the province. 
Also present at the plenum, which is underway right now at the 
municipal CTC's [Cuban Workers Federation] theater, is Pedro 
Ross, member of the Politburo and secretary general of the CTC, 
who has asked the provincial union secretaries to report on the 
main proposals made by the provincial workers at their 
respective Parliament in the Workplace assemblies. 
  [Begin Ross recording] At that assembly, they even said that 
yes, we must sell the rum at a high price, and we must sell 
cigarettes at a high price, because after all, we do have 
profiteers and we have people who buy... [pauses] that if we set 
the price at five pesos, such people would buy up the entire 
(?supply). We should therefore sell the cigarettes at 20 pesos. 
  So, then, if we wish to stop the profiteers, and if I am a 
revolutionary and wish to help the Revolution, and yet want to 
(?smoke) an extra box of cigarettes, I won't let myself... 
[pauses] (?instead of from the) profiteer, I will buy it from 
the Revolution, because that money will be used for the 
Revolution. That is one of the things the workers said. 
  And I cannot sell bottles of rum freely [por la libre]. 
Openly, the cost is some 15 pesos. If we really wish to save and 
contribute, we need to place the bottles of rum so that if I, or 
other revolutionary people, wish to drink a bottle of rum, we 
will have a place to get it where rum will cost 120, or even 130 
pesos -- just like what they sell it for in the streets -- 
because that is the only way to stop the profiteers. [end 
recording] 
  Regarding the delicate matter of rationing the work force, 
Pedro Ross explained that to date, the only sectors authorized 
to take such a step are tourism and transportation, and that it 
will never be valid without the presence of the union. 
  I reiterate, friends: The plenum at the end of the 
Parliaments in the Workplace assemblies in Santiago de Cuba 
Province is underway right now, here, with Politburo members 
Esteban Lazo Hernandez and Pedro Ross Leal in attendance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

