<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   IMF Approves Government Economic Program for 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803201294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0051 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 17 Mar (EFE) -- Financial sources report 
that the IMF has approved the Uruguayan Government economic 
program for 1994. The program predicts a 36 percent inflation 
rate and a monetary devaluation of 27 percent for the year. 
  The forecasted inflation rate involves controlling prices: 
In 
1993 it totalled 52.68 percent. 
  The planned monetary devaluation remains at previous levels; 
in 1993 it totalled 26.88 percent. 
  The IMF experts finished studying the economic program in 
early March. Next month the IMF board will analyze the economic 
situation in Uruguay. 
  Once IMF approval is received, Uruguay will have important 
support abroad that will create confidence among potential 
foreign investors and allow the country to obtain credit lines 
from other international organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11334 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat054_s_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803223194 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803223194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 17 
March. 
  The central government registered a $31 million surplus in 
January, which is substantially lower than the same month last 
year, when it was $71.7 million. The central government's fiscal 
deficit was $127.6 million in 1993. (Montevideo BUSQUEDA in 
Spanish 3 Mar 94 p 18) 
  The National Statistics Institute reported that in January 
the minimum salary was readjusted 2.36 percent for the private 
sector and 10.46 percent for public employees. The real salary 
increased 1.85 percent above the 3.41 percent January inflation 
rate. (Montevideo BUSQUEDA in Spanish 3 Mar 94 pp 22, 23) 
  The Inter-American Development Bank on 9 March approved a 
$30 
million loan to implement a program designed to improve social, 
health, education, and labor policies, and to modernize court 
administration. (Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 10 Mar 94 p 12) 
  The executive branch eliminated the tax on the purchase of 
foreign currencies used for foreign exchange activities by 
public banks. The banks affected by the measure are the 
Uruguayan Central Bank, the Bank of Uruguay, and the Uruguayan 
Mortgage Bank. (Montevideo Radio Carve in Spanish 0000 GMT 17 
Mar 94) 

</TEXT>

