<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders To Discuss Suspension of Constitutional Revision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2003010894 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 19 Mar 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PY2003010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- The future of the constitutional 
revision process will be decided on 22 March during a meeting of 
party leaders and Congress President Senator Humberto Lucena 
(PMDB-PB [Brazilian Democratic Movement Party-Paraiba]). The 
suggestion to hold the meeting to see whether the constitutional 
revision process takes off once and for all was made by the PMDB 
leader in the lower house, Deputy Tarcicio Delgado (MG [Minas 
Gerais]), who believes the work will not continue. 
  "Either the constitutional revision is made, or it is not. 
We 
must make a decision in order not to act like clowns. Right now, 
attention is centered on the economic plan, the stripping of the 
political rights of congressmen, and the election race," Delgado 
said. 
  The proposal of PSDB [Brazilian Social Democracy Party] 
leader Deputy Artur da Tavola (RJ [Rio de Janeiro]) to suspend 
the constitutional revision work after voting on subjects of 
consensus and to resume the work in 1995 is gaining force in 
Congress. Tavola believes he has found a formula to make the 
proposal legally feasible. He maintains that the power to amend 
the Constitution could be delegated to another congress by 
including an article in the chapter of temporary provisions of 
the Constitution. 
  Deputy Miro Teixeira [PDT [Democratic Labor Party]-RJ) 
agrees 
with constitutional revision rapporteur Deputy Nelson Jobim 
(PMDB-RS [Rio Grande do Sul]) that any proposal to suspend the 
work is unconstitutional. He said the anticipated promulgation 
of the Social Emergency Fund (FSE) has frozen the deadline of 
the revision work in order to prevent questioning by the STF 
[Federal Supreme Court]. 

</TEXT>

