<H3> <TI>   Salinas Marks Oil Nationalization Anniversary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003135294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2003135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Elizabeth Diaz from the "ACIR Radio News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] President Carlos Salinas de Gortari affirmed that 
his administration has fulfilled its commitment to keep the oil 
industry under Mexican control and ownership. He added that 
Pemex [Mexican Petroleum] had been restructured and strengthened 
because, otherwise, it would have deteriorated into an 
unproductive and weak corporation thereby becoming easy prey for 
local and foreign, private interests. 
  At midday today at the main Pemex administration offices, 
President Salinas led the ceremonies marking the 56th oil 
nationalization anniversary. This was the sixth and last [Pemex] 
public ceremony the president will attend before his term in 
office expires. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] The government's responsibility 
toward this enterprise can only be fulfilled if we establish 
conditions that guarantee Pemex's future permanence as a 
nationalized enterprise. We have worked expressly to fulfill 
that duty and the facts prove this. I hereby state that Pemex is 
stronger because it is more productive and efficient. On the 
domestic front, Pemex can guarantee the country's energy needs; 
it strengthens the public economy for social spending; it 
increases its own reserves and investments; and restructures its 
activities. Pemex's fortitude is enhanced abroad because we did 
not allow any international relationship whatsoever that could 
subjugate Pemex decisions to any other will than that of the 
Mexican people. [end recording] 
  Cabinet members and representatives of government branches, 
workers unions, and business organizations attended the 
ceremony. The president recognized Pemex General Director 
Francisco Rojas' honesty and dedication. He stressed that he 
will keep his commitment to keep Mexican oil in the Mexican 
people's hands for our exclusive benefit until the very last day 
of his administration. 

</TEXT>

