<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuevo Leon, Tamaulipas Made Migrant Entry Points </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003131494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2225 GMT 18 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2003131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Reynosa, 18 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Foreigners who wish to 
travel through Mexico to other countries as migrants will only 
be able to enter the country at customs stations in Colombia, 
Nuevo Leon and Lucio Blanco-Los Indios de Matamoros, Tamaulipas 
beginning next Monday. 
  In a communique issued by the Mexican Consulate in McAllen, 
Texas, the Mexican Finance and Public Credit Secretariat (SHCP) 
said this measure had been agreed upon to avoid the jams that 
have occurred at the Reynosa and Matamoros, Tamaulipas custom 
stations. The document explained that they are trying to ease 
and control the international movement of people and merchandise 
from the United States to Central American countries through 
Mexican territory. 
  Based on Article 116 paragraph one of the Customs Law, 
foreigners who want to enter Mexico at border points between 
Acuna, Coahuila and Matamoros, Tamaulipas will be able to do so 
at the previously mentioned customs stations. 
  The SHCP also said the Lucio Blanco-Los Indios crossing is 
part of the Matamoros Customs Office and the facilities at the 
Colombia, Nuevo Leon Customs Office are adequate and are open 24 
hours a day. 
  The communique said that once foreigners are given migrant 
status, they can take their equipment with them but they will 
have to request a 10-day temporary permit for the vehicle they 
are travelling in. It added that people interested in moving 
merchandise through Mexico should consult a customs agent, who 
will take care of the necessary procedures at both customs 
offices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11357 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat054_c_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-054 </AU>
