<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Accept Budget Cut, Not Volunteer Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1903030394 Tegucigalpa EL PERIODICO DE HONDURAS in Spanish 
16 Mar 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PA1903030394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa EL PERIODICO DE HONDURAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Honduran Armed Forces said they would accept a 
budget reduction, an eventual privatization of Hondutel 
[Honduran Telecommunications Enterprise], and any other 
presidential initiative, but they also clearly established their 
opposition to an all-voluntary military service. 
  General Luis Alonso Discua Elvir acknowledged that health 
and 
education are priorities and expressed the Armed Forces' 
willingness to support President Reina's decision to implement 
the social assistance program he promised the Honduran people. 
  The planned 10-percent reduction of the Armed Forces' 270 
million lempira budget represents a 27 million-lempira cut 
which, according to Discua Elvir, will negatively affect the 
military's community programs. 
  Right now the military is engaged in assistance programs to 
improve education, environmental protection, and health, which 
includes the vaccination of the canine population. 
  Regarding an eventual privatization of Hondutel, the 
military 
chief said: "This is a profitable enterprise that has been very 
good for the government. Any eventual privatization should be 
carefully analyzed." The Armed Forces, however, acknowledge 
that "the final decision rests with the executive branch." 
  Discua Elvir announced that he will ask the Comptroller 
General's Office to audit the offices managed by the Armed 
Forces, something that has been done since 1990. 
  The military commander reiterated his opposition to military 
service becoming an all-volunteer institution because he 
believes it would be the end of the Armed Forces. 
  Gen. Discua is of the opinion that military service must be 
"constitutional and educational" (obligatory), but a 
presidential promise describes it as "voluntary and educational." 
  On this point, as on others, the military chief concedes 
that 
the final decision is in the hands of the president of Honduras. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11361 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat054_i_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

