<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Dispute With Costa Rica `Very Serious' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1803134094 Managua Radio Corporacion in Spanish 1200 GMT 
18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1803134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Corporacion </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Six o'Clock Sharp" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Nicaraguan international law specialists believe the 
current border situation with Costa Rica, where local 
landholders are invading part of Nicaragua, is extremely 
serious, and that the government must immediately and thoroughly 
act to clarify once and for all the sovereignty of their 
homeland along the border, including the San Juan River. 
  The Foreign Ministry pointed out that the Sandinist National 
Liberation Front is directly responsible for the current border 
situation because during the war it displaced the peasants and 
shopkeepers from the area and even mined part of it. Therefore, 
Nicaraguans moved to the other side of the border, to Costa 
Rica, where they helped to develop Costa Rica. After that, the 
Sandinists completely ignored the strip between boundary posts 
13 and 14, almost 30 km, which was abandoned. Nicaragua has 
warned Costa Rica that if it does not pay attention to marking 
out the area, it would unilaterally do so next April. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

