<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gore's Removing Coca Leaf Necklace Viewed as `Snub' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2103021894 Havana Cuba Vision Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 
21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2103021894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Cuba Vision Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Vice President Al Gore removed a coca-leaf 
necklace that had been placed in homage around his neck upon his 
arrival at the airport in La Paz, capital of Bolivia. The 
incident was interpreted by Bolivian radio as an inadmissable 
snub, a grave insult to Bolivia, because the coca leaf is 
considered an element of the national culture. 
  The U.S. vice president's attitude is due to Washington's 
position that the origin of the drug-addiction problem affecting 
U.S. society lies in the existence of the coca leaf. 
  The coca leaf has been consumed for centuries for beneficial 
purposes, but now the U.S. is trying to bring about the total 
elimination of the plant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

