<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. State Department `Threatens' Traders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1803142294 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 1300 GMT 18 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1803142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the Argentine city of Mar del Plata, Cuban Vice 
President Jose Ramon Fernandez has charged that the U.S. State 
Department has circulated threats against businessmen who intend 
to trade with Cuba. After calling the blockade the U.S. 
maintains against Cuba for over three decades criminal, 
Fernandez said that, despite those pressures, every day there 
are more and more foreign investors, particularly in tourism and 
petroleum exploration. Fernandez was attending a Panamerican 
Sports Organization meeting in Mar del Plata. 

</TEXT>

