<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Treasury Bonds To Be Offered to Creditor Banks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1903014294 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
18 Mar 94 Economic Section p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1903014294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Ana Maria Mandim] </F>
  [Text] New York -- Finance Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso on 17 March admitted that Brazil will use its 
international reserves to purchase U.S. Treasury bonds for a 
total of $2.8 billion. These bonds will be offered to creditor 
banks as guarantees during the exchange of old foreign debt 
bonds for new ones with better repayment conditions. Cardoso 
said Brazil is prepared to produce the necessary bonds to 
guarantee an agreement with creditor banks on 15 April. 
  William Rhodes, president of the Creditor Banks Advisory 
Committee and Citibank vice president, said at the end of his 
meeting with the minister that he will consult with the 
committee today, seeking to waive a clause in the agreement 
requiring the purchase of those bonds directly from the U.S. 
Treasury. He will also seek to do away with the requirement of 
an IMF stand-by agreement for the purchase of those bonds. 
  In a note distributed after the meeting, Rhodes said: "We 
are 
consulting with the committee seeking the approval of the 
necessary exemptions (waivers) in order to put together a 
package to finance the foreign debt on 15 April, as agreed. I 
trust tomorrow afternoon (today) at the latest, the committee 
will be ready to recommend the approval of the waivers to the 
international financial community." 
  Standing next to the minister in the Intercontinental 
Hotel's 
lobby, Rhodes said: "I trust the committee will maintain the 
agreement to renegotiate the debt." The minister admitted that 
the country has purchased, is purchasing, and will continue to 
purchase bonds to shore up the negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

