<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRENSA LATINA Views Gore Visit to South America </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bolivian Peasant, Workers Bodies Reject Visit </H4>
<F P=102> PA1903202294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1857 GMT 19 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1903202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] La Paz, 18 Mar [date as received] (PL) -- Vice 
President Albert Gore's 12-hour flash visit to Bolivia was the 
subject of more expressions of rejection by the country's 
leading peasant and workers organizations. 
  Felix Santos, top leader of the Sole Peasant Workers 
Confederation of Bolivia (CSUTCB), condemned Gore's visit, 
because he believes the vice president is coming to press for 
the forced elimination of coca plantations and the complete 
privatization of the country's economy. 
  There is reason to fear he is coming to promote violence 
against peasants who grow coca, a leaf with natural benefits 
which is also used to produce cocaine, Santos added, referring 
to the growing tension between narcotics police and peasants 
over the last few weeks. The peasants are afraid the soldiers 
will come to flatten their crops. 
  Washington has conditioned its aid program of the Bolivian 
balance of payment, which totals $40 million per year, to the 
fulfillment of coca plantation reduction goals. 
  Toribio Hinojosa, secretary general of the Bolivian Workers 
Federation (COB) [Central Obrera Boliviana], has said the 
organization has decided to declare Al Gore's visit as non 
grata, adding the visit demonstrates U.S. concern over the 
peasants' determination to resist the elimination of the coca 
leaf. 
  The government and the coca leaf growers are on the verge of 
an agreement that conditions coca plantation reduction plans to 
the development of alternate activities to provide farmers with 
new means of survival, thus reducing tension. 
  During his stay in Bolivia, Gore will meet with Bolivian 
President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada and other national 
authorities, under strict security measures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

